This paper discusses privacy implications and fingerprinting algorithms, which are commonly studied in the computer security (cs.CR) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. The paper also evaluates the effectiveness of these algorithms on real-world datasets, which falls under the scope of data mining (cs.SI) and databases (cs.DB). Additionally, the paper addresses constraints on the number of attributes that can be queried about individuals, which could be relevant to the sub-categories of cryptography (cs.CY) and human-computer interaction (cs.HC). However, since the focus is primarily on privacy and fingerprinting algorithms, cs.CR and cs.LG are the most likely sub-categories.
